      <section class="methodology-section">
        <h2>Key Calculations</h2>

        <div class="source-card">
          <h3>Cigarette Equivalence</h3>
          <p class="claim">"Breathing air with 22 µg/m³ of PM2.5 carries the same <em>mortality risk</em> as smoking 1 cigarette per day."</p>
          <div class="source-details">
            <p><strong>Source:</strong> Berkeley Earth analysis by Richard Muller and Elizabeth Muller</p>
            <p><strong>What this means:</strong> This is a <em>mortality risk equivalence</em>, not a chemical equivalence. PM2.5 and cigarette smoke are completely different—different carcinogens, different exposure pathways. What's equivalent is the increased risk of death: ~1.4% increase per cigarette/day ≈ ~1.4% increase per 22 µg/m³ PM2.5.</p>
            <p><strong>Calculation:</strong> PM2.5 concentration (µg/m³) ÷ 22 = cigarettes/day mortality-risk equivalent</p>
            <p><strong>Why we use it:</strong> It's a vivid way to communicate risk, not a scientific statement about exposure.</p>
            <a href="http://berkeleyearth.org/air-pollution-and-cigarette-equivalence/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Berkeley Earth: Air Pollution and Cigarette Equivalence →</a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="source-card">
          <h3>Life Expectancy Reduction</h3>
          <p class="claim">"Every 10 µg/m³ of PM2.5 above WHO guidelines reduces life expectancy by ~0.98 years."</p>
          <div class="source-details">
            <p><strong>Source:</strong> Air Quality Life Index (AQLI), University of Chicago Energy Policy Institute</p>
            <p><strong>Methodology:</strong> Based on analysis of China's Huai River heating policy natural experiment and subsequent global extrapolation. The policy created a sharp discontinuity in pollution levels, allowing causal estimation of PM2.5's effect on mortality.</p>
            <p><strong>Calculation:</strong> ((PM2.5 concentration - 5) ÷ 10) × 0.98 = years of life lost over lifetime</p>
            <p><strong>Key assumption:</strong> 70-year lifetime exposure at current concentration levels.</p>
            <p><strong>About "hours lost per day":</strong> This is a <em>lifetime equivalent</em> spread across each day, not actual hours lost today. If PM2.5 stays at X µg/m³ for your entire life, you'd lose Y years total—we convert that to a daily figure for illustration.</p>
            <a href="https://aqli.epic.uchicago.edu/the-index/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">AQLI Methodology →</a>
            <a href="https://www.pnas.org/doi/10.1073/pnas.1616784114" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Original PNAS Paper (Ebenstein et al., 2017) →</a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="source-card">
          <h3>WHO Guideline: 5 µg/m³</h3>
          <p class="claim">"WHO recommends annual PM2.5 levels not exceed 5 µg/m³."</p>
          <div class="source-details">
            <p><strong>Source:</strong> WHO Global Air Quality Guidelines, 2021</p>
            <p><strong>Previous guideline:</strong> 10 µg/m³ (2005)</p>
            <p><strong>Why it changed:</strong> Updated evidence showed health effects at lower concentrations than previously understood. There is no known safe threshold.</p>
            <a href="https://www.who.int/publications/i/item/9789240034228" target="_blank" rel="noopener">WHO Air Quality Guidelines 2021 →</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="methodology-section">
        <h2>Health Claims</h2>

        <div class="source-card">
          <h3>Children Receive Higher Dose Per Body Weight</h3>
          <p class="claim">"Children absorb ~40% more PM2.5 per kilogram of body weight."</p>
          <div class="source-details">
            <p><strong>Source:</strong> Multiple studies confirm children receive higher doses:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Children breathe 20-30 times per minute vs 12-20 for adults</li>
              <li>Higher ventilation rate relative to body size</li>
              <li>Study found children exposed to 122%-175% of adult PM2.5 levels in urban walking scenarios</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Our multiplier (1.4x):</strong> Conservative estimate within the documented range.</p>
            <a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S221209552200116X" target="_blank" rel="noopener">PM2.5 exposure differences between children and adults →</a>
            <a href="https://ww2.arb.ca.gov/resources/inhalable-particulate-matter-and-health" target="_blank" rel="noopener">California Air Resources Board: Particulate Matter and Health →</a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="source-card">
          <h3>PM2.5 Enters the Bloodstream and Brain</h3>
          <p class="claim">"PM2.5 particles pass through your lungs into your blood. They reach your brain."</p>
          <div class="source-details">
            <p><strong>Sources:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>Particles &lt;2.5µm can cross the alveolar-capillary barrier</li>
              <li>Ultrafine particles detected in brain tissue via two pathways: blood-brain barrier crossing and direct olfactory nerve transport</li>
              <li>Landmark Oberdörster et al. (2004) study demonstrated translocation of inhaled ultrafine particles to the brain in animal models</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Timing:</strong> Translocation occurs within hours to days, not minutes.</p>
            <a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9491465/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">A review of PM2.5-induced brain damage (PMC) →</a>
            <a href="https://ehp.niehs.nih.gov/doi/10.1289/ehp.7054" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Oberdörster et al.: Translocation of Inhaled Ultrafine Particles to the Brain →</a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="source-card">
          <h3>Particle Retention in Lungs</h3>
          <p class="claim">"Black carbon lodges in lung tissue."</p>
          <div class="source-details">
            <p><strong>Source:</strong> Autopsy studies show particulate matter accumulation in lung tissue, particularly black carbon.</p>
            <p><strong>Nuance:</strong> Not all particles stay "forever." The body has clearance mechanisms (mucociliary clearance, macrophage uptake). However:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Clearance is incomplete, especially for ultrafine particles</li>
              <li>Some particles translocate to lymph nodes and other organs</li>
              <li>Chronic exposure overwhelms clearance capacity</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Accuracy:</strong> Some particles are cleared, but chronic exposure overwhelms the body's clearance capacity. Many particles persist.</p>
            <a href="https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJM199312093292401" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Dockery et al.: An Association between Air Pollution and Mortality (Six Cities Study) →</a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="source-card">
          <h3>Benzene Carcinogenicity</h3>
          <p class="claim">"Benzene causes leukemia. There is no safe level."</p>
          <div class="source-details">
            <p><strong>Source:</strong> IARC (International Agency for Research on Cancer) classifies benzene as Group 1 carcinogen (carcinogenic to humans).</p>
            <p><strong>WHO position:</strong> "No safe level of exposure can be recommended."</p>
            <a href="https://www.who.int/publications/i/item/9789240000278" target="_blank" rel="noopener">WHO Air Quality Guidelines for Europe: Benzene →</a>
            <a href="https://monographs.iarc.fr/list-of-classifications" target="_blank" rel="noopener">IARC Carcinogen Classifications →</a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="source-card">
          <h3>Lead and IQ</h3>
          <p class="claim">"Lead exposure lowers IQ in children."</p>
          <div class="source-details">
            <p><strong>Source:</strong> Lead exposure is well-documented to reduce IQ. Meta-analyses show ~2-3 IQ points lost per 10 µg/dL increase in blood lead.</p>
            <p><strong>Mechanism:</strong> Lead disrupts neurodevelopment, particularly in developing brains. There is no known safe threshold for lead exposure in children.</p>
            <p><strong>Air pollution link:</strong> Lead can be present in PM2.5, particularly near industrial areas and from legacy contamination.</p>
            <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15862083/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Lanphear et al.: Low-Level Environmental Lead Exposure and Children's Intellectual Function →</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

