      <section class="methodology-section">
        <h2>Data Validation</h2>

        <div class="source-card">
          <h3>How We Verify Data Quality</h3>
          <p class="claim">Sensors lie. APIs fail. We validate everything.</p>
          <div class="source-details">
            <p>Our validation system runs multiple checks on every data point:</p>

            <p><strong>API Response Validation</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>Verify WAQI response structure is valid JSON with expected fields</li>
              <li>Check for error codes (999 = WAQI error, "-" = no data)</li>
              <li>Validate timestamp presence and format</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>Value Bounds Checking</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>PM2.5 must be 0-1000 µg/m³ (values above 1000 are likely sensor errors)</li>
              <li>AQI must be 0-500 on US EPA scale</li>
              <li>Flag suspiciously low values (&lt;5 µg/m³ is rare in India)</li>
              <li>Flag exact zeros (sensors rarely read exactly 0)</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>Anomaly Detection</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Outlier detection:</strong> If a station reads &gt;3x or &lt;0.2x the city median, flag it</li>
              <li><strong>Flatline detection:</strong> Exactly 0 readings suggest sensor malfunction</li>
              <li><strong>Round number detection:</strong> Suspiciously round values (e.g., 100, 200) may be placeholders</li>
            </ul>

            <p><strong>Freshness Checks</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>Data older than 2 hours is marked as stale</li>
              <li>Stale stations are included but flagged in quality reports</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

