      <section class="methodology-section">
        <h2>Historical Trends & National Aggregates</h2>

        <div class="source-card">
          <h3>The "How Have We Been Getting Fucked?" Chart</h3>
          <p class="claim">Shows 30-day national PM2.5 trends with population-weighted averages across major Indian cities.</p>
          <div class="source-details">
            <p><strong>What you see:</strong> A bar chart showing daily national average PM2.5 for the last 30 days, with a reference line at the WHO guideline (5 µg/m³).</p>
            <p><strong>Colors indicate severity:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li><span style="color: #22c55e;">■</span> Green (≤12 µg/m³) — Within US EPA "Good" range</li>
              <li><span style="color: #eab308;">■</span> Yellow (12-35 µg/m³) — Unhealthy for sensitive groups</li>
              <li><span style="color: #f97316;">■</span> Orange (35-55 µg/m³) — Unhealthy</li>
              <li><span style="color: #dc2626;">■</span> Red (>55 µg/m³) — Very unhealthy to hazardous</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Stats shown:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>30-day avg:</strong> Simple average of daily weighted PM2.5</li>
              <li><strong>Days above WHO:</strong> Count of days where average exceeded 5 µg/m³</li>
              <li><strong>Worst day:</strong> Highest PM2.5 reading in the period</li>
              <li><strong>vs last week:</strong> Percentage change comparing last 7 days to previous 7 days</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="source-card">
          <h3>Population-Weighted Averaging</h3>
          <p class="claim">"National average" isn't a simple mean—it's weighted by population exposed.</p>
          <div class="source-details">
            <p><strong>Why this matters:</strong> Delhi's PM2.5 matters more than a smaller city's because more people are breathing it. A simple average would underrepresent the true population health burden.</p>
            <p><strong>Formula:</strong></p>
            <pre class="code-block">weighted_avg = Σ(city_pm25 × city_population) ÷ Σ(city_population)</pre>
            <p><strong>Cities included:</strong> Delhi, Mumbai, Kolkata, Bangalore, Chennai, Hyderabad, Ahmedabad, Patna, Lucknow, Agra</p>
            <p><strong>Combined population:</strong> ~150 million people</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="source-card">
          <h3>Consecutive Days Above WHO ("The Streak")</h3>
          <p class="claim">Counts how many days in a row national PM2.5 has exceeded the WHO guideline of 5 µg/m³.</p>
          <div class="source-details">
            <p><strong>Why we show this:</strong> It's one thing to say "air is bad." It's another to say "we haven't had a single safe day in 47 days." The streak counter makes the chronic nature of the problem visceral.</p>
            <p><strong>Calculation:</strong> Starting from today, count backwards until we find a day where weighted average PM2.5 ≤ 5 µg/m³. In practice, this number is often... large.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="source-card">
          <h3>Year-over-Year Comparison</h3>
          <p class="claim">Compares current 30-day period to the same period last year.</p>
          <div class="source-details">
            <p><strong>What it shows:</strong> Whether air quality is better or worse than the same time last year. Seasonality matters (winter is worse), so comparing equivalent periods is more meaningful.</p>
            <p><strong>Limitation:</strong> Requires at least 1 year of historical data to display. May not show in early data collection phases.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

