        <div class="source-card">
          <h3>Data Sources</h3>
          <div class="source-details">
            <p><strong>Real-time (WAQI):</strong> World Air Quality Index API provides hourly readings from CPCB stations. Used for live dashboard and ongoing data collection.</p>
            <p><strong>Historical backfill (OpenAQ):</strong> OpenAQ v3 API provides historical PM2.5 data going back several years. Used to populate historical trends before our data collection started.</p>
            <p><strong>Why two sources?</strong> WAQI has better real-time coverage and station information. OpenAQ has deeper historical archives. We use WAQI for ongoing collection and OpenAQ for historical backfill.</p>
            <a href="https://aqicn.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">WAQI API →</a>
            <a href="https://openaq.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">OpenAQ API →</a>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="source-card">
          <h3>Database Schema</h3>
          <div class="source-details">
            <p><strong>Storage:</strong> Cloudflare D1 (SQLite at the edge)</p>
            <p><strong>Key tables:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li><code>city_snapshots</code> — Hourly snapshots of each city's PM2.5</li>
              <li><code>daily_aggregates</code> — Daily min/max/avg per city</li>
              <li><code>national_daily_aggregates</code> — Pre-computed national averages</li>
              <li><code>openaq_stations</code> — Mapping of OpenAQ stations to our cities</li>
              <li><code>ingestion_log</code> — Audit trail of data collection runs</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Why pre-compute?</strong> Calculating population-weighted averages across millions of readings on every page load would be slow. We pre-compute daily aggregates via background workers.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="source-card">
          <h3>Background Workers</h3>
          <div class="source-details">
            <p>Three Cloudflare Workers handle data collection and aggregation:</p>
            <p><strong>1. Ingestion Worker</strong> (hourly cron)</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Fetches current PM2.5 from WAQI for all cities</li>
              <li>Validates data quality (bounds, freshness, anomalies)</li>
              <li>Stores in <code>city_snapshots</code> and <code>readings</code></li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>2. Aggregator Worker</strong> (hourly cron, 15min offset)</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Computes daily aggregates from city snapshots</li>
              <li>Calculates population-weighted national average</li>
              <li>Stores in <code>daily_aggregates</code> and <code>national_daily_aggregates</code></li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>3. Backfill Worker</strong> (manual HTTP trigger)</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Imports historical data from OpenAQ</li>
              <li>Maps OpenAQ stations to our cities by geocoordinates</li>
              <li>Designed for one-time historical import</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="source-card">
          <h3>Station-to-City Mapping</h3>
          <div class="source-details">
            <p><strong>Challenge:</strong> OpenAQ has thousands of Indian stations with inconsistent naming. We need to map them to our cities.</p>
            <p><strong>Solution:</strong> Geographic proximity matching:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>For each OpenAQ station, calculate distance to our city centers</li>
              <li>If within 50km radius, assign to that city</li>
              <li>Multiple stations per city are averaged</li>
